05994nam a22008295i 9780801458736DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014587367 a10.7591/97808014587362doi  a(DE-B1597)527054  a(OCoLC)1100455412  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aBUS0450002bisacsh04a332.4/97304aThe Future of the Dollar /ced. by Jonathan Kirshner, Eric Helleiner. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b14 tables, 5 charts/graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Money00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFIGURES AND TABLES -- tPREFACE -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- t1. The Future of the Dollar:Whither the Key Currency? -- t2. The Enduring International Preeminence of the Dollar -- t3. U.S. Current Account Deficits and the Dollar Standard’s Sustainability: A Monetary Approach -- t4. Enduring Top Currency, Fragile Negotiated Currency: Politics and the Dollar’s International Role -- t5. Housing Finance, Growth, and the U.S. Dollar’s Surprising Durability -- t6. From Monopoly to Oligopoly: Lessons from the Pre-1914 Experience -- t7. Toward a Leaderless Currency System -- t8. Twenty-First Century Geopolitics and the Erosion of the Dollar Order -- t9. After the (Relative) Fall: Dollar Diminution and the Consequences for American Power -- t10. Summing Up and Looking Ahead: The Future of the Future of the Dollar -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor half a century, the United States has garnered substantial political and economic benefits as a result of the dollar's de facto role as a global currency. In recent years, however, the dollar's preponderant position in world markets has come under challenge. The dollar has been more volatile than ever against foreign currencies, and various nations have switched to non-dollar instruments in their transactions. China and the Arab Gulf states continue to hold massive amounts of U.S. government obligations, in effect subsidizing U.S. current account deficits, and those holdings are a point of potential vulnerability for American policy.What is the future of the U.S. dollar as an international currency? Will predictions of its demise end up just as inaccurate as those that have accompanied major international financial crises since the early 1970s? Analysts disagree, often profoundly, in their answers to these questions. In The Future of the Dollar, leading scholars of dollar's international role bring multidisciplinary perspectives and a range of contrasting predictions to the question of the dollar's future. This timely book provides readers with a clear sense of why such disagreements exist and it outlines a variety of future scenarios and the possible political implications for the United States and the world.Contributors: David Calleo, The Johns Hopkins University; Benjamin Cohen, University of California, Santa Barbara; Marcello de Cecco, Scuola Normale Superiore di Pisa, Italy; Eric Helleiner, University of Waterloo; Harold James, Princeton University and European University Institute; Jonathan Kirshner, Cornell University; Ronald I. McKinnon, Stanford University; Herman Schwartz, University of Virginia  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aBusiness (General). 4aGeneral Economics. 4aInternational Studies. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Money & Monetary Policy.2bisacsh1 aCalleo, David P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCecco, Marcello de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Benjamin J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelleiner, Eric, econtributor.4c